HEADWORD: Eros
<hw>E"ros</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/
love, <?/ (personified) Eros, fr. <?/ to love.]</ety> <fld>(Greek
Myth.)</fld> <def>Love; the god of love; -- by earlier writers
represented as one of the first and creative gods, by later writers as
the son of Aphrodite, equivalent to the Latin god Cupid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

